With a record number of people being displaced from their homes due to conflict, climate change and more, we sat down with the CEO and Founder of @safehaven_va Egette Indelele to discuss her efforts to provide mental health services to refugee and immigrant youth.

Ahead of World Refugee Day on June 20th, Safe Haven wants to hear from you on how this community has positively impacted your life. Follow the hashtag #DecreaseStigmaIncreaseConnectionsForRefugees to learn more!

node.title: World Refugee Day: A Conversation With @egette_tnz

node.text:
The lives of hundreds of millions of children have been upended by coronavirus. With schools closed and coronavirus spreading across the world, hundreds of millions of children are trapped indoors. 
Parents and kids face many challenges as they adjust to working and learning from home. The transition while maintaining physical distance from friends, colleagues, teachers and extended family has placed great strain on kids. Keeping kids focused on their education can provide the reassuring structure and emotional support that will get them through this unprecedented time.

Here, UNICEF's Global Education Chief Robert Jenkins offers 5 tips for parents on how to keep their children learning and help them cope.

node.title: How to Help Kids Cope with Coronavirus

node.text: What makes a city "child friendly"? We sat down with former National #ChildFriendlyCities Initiative Youth Advisor @abdullahakll to discuss the long-term goal of engaging youth and prioritizing child well-being in cities across the U.S.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by UNICEF USA on August 12, 2021. May be an image of 3 people and outdoors.

node.text:
A Year of #ChildFriendlyCities: Today's International #YouthDay marks the first anniversary of the Child Friendly Cities Initiative (CFCI) in the U.S. As the initial cohort, six local governments signed on to put children first and to address the immediate needs of young people in Houston; Minneapolis; San Francisco; Johnson City, Tenn.; Decatur, Ga. and Prince George's County, Md. Today, CFCI is making a difference in the lives of nearly 1 million children and young people in these pilot cities. To see some of this work in action, check out our link in bio!

Pictured here, this mural painted by artist Daas in 2020 in downtown Johnson City, Tenn., features three children planting the seeds for a future rich in diversity and racial equality.

📸: © JT McSpadden

⁠
When your Club registers, you'll receive a #BackToSchool kit full of materials and resources for a successful year of advocating, speaking out, fundraising and building community on behalf of UNICEF! Check out our link in bio for more info.

When the #Beirut port explosion happened last year, 12-year-old Marilyn was at home alone with her younger siblings. With UNICEF-supported mental health support, she's made a lot of progress in her recovery from the event.

"It’s important now to look forward to the future, but we can’t ignore the past," she says. "It makes us who we are."

📸: @uniceflebanon

Menstrual hygiene is a real problem in Mauritania because of the lack of sanitation facilities and information — pushing many young girls to drop out of school. But at the UNICEF-supported Dar Naim girls' activity center on the outskirts of Nouakchott, teenage girls and young women learn how to sew reusable cloth sanitary pads.

"I am participating for the first time in the sanitary pad making workshop," says 23-year-old Aliya. "It is very important for us young girls because we don't have access to quality pads, so often we have to manage as we can."

📸: unicefmauritanie

Even before the #COVID19 pandemic, children around the world faced education barriers due to financial difficulty. Thanks to a UNICEF-supported scholarship, 16-year-old Olivia can continue learning against all odds. "I’m so happy I had this opportunity to go to school," she says. "My dream is to become a pharmacist."

#ForEveryChild, opportunity.
📸: @unicef_burkinafaso

This #WorldBreastfeedingWeek, we're celebrating moms like Jane Gama from Malawi, who breastfeeds her daughter to help make sure she has the best start in life.⁠
⁠
#Breastfeeding is natural, but it isn't always easy. That's why @UNICEF and the World Health Organization are calling on governments and all partners to share responsibility for prioritizing breastfeeding-friendly environments for nursing mothers and their babies. Check out our link in bio to learn more.⁠
⁠
📸: @unicefmalawi

Five million people in Ethiopia's Tigray region rely on aid to eat — but without humanitarian access, UNICEF predicts 100,000 children face life-threatening malnutrition this year alone.⁠
